            </svg>
        </div>
        <div class="col-3"><h3>Sign Up</h3></div>
        <div class="col-7">
            <p>Create an account on Chemical Twins in order to access all the functionalities of the application. You will be able to upload experiments as well as 
                creating and joining livestream. In case you don't want to do that do not worry, you will still be able to view past experiments in the website uploaded by other users
                but you won't be able to upload your own.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-2">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="90" height="90" fill="currentColor" class="bi bi-wrench-adjustable-circle" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
                <path d="M12.496 8a4.491 4.491 0 0 1-1.703 3.526L9.497 8.5l2.959-1.11c.027.2.04.403.04.61Z"/>
                <path d="M16 8A8 8 0 1 1 0 8a8 8 0 0 1 16 0Zm-1 0a7 7 0 1 0-13.202 3.249l1.988-1.657a4.5 4.5 0 0 1 7.537-4.623L7.497 6.5l1 2.5 1.333 3.11c-.56.251-1.18.39-1.833.39a4.49 4.49 0 0 1-1.592-.29L4.747 14.2A7 7 0 0 0 15 8Zm-8.295.139a.25.25 0 0 0-.288-.376l-1.5.5.159.474.808-.27-.595.894a.25.25 0 0 0 .287.376l.808-.27-.595.894a.25.25 0 0 0 .287.376l1.5-.5-.159-.474-.808.27.596-.894a.25.25 0 0 0-.288-.376l-.808.27.596-.894Z"/>
            </svg>
        </div>
        <div class="col-3"><h3>Raspberry PI</h3></div>
        <div class="col-7">
            <p>Chemical Twins works together with any Raspberry PI board, so all you need is to connect your board to the internet and download the following 
                <a href="script/connect.py" download>script</a> and use it on your PI in order to send and receive data from the application
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-2">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="90" height="90" fill="currentColor" class="bi bi-filetype-py" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
                <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M14 4.5V14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H7v-1h5a1 1 0 0 0 1-1V4.5h-2A1.5 1.5 0 0 1 9.5 3V1H4a1 1 0 0 0-1 1v9H2V2a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h5.5L14 4.5ZM0 11.85h1.6c.289 0 .533.06.732.179.201.117.355.276.46.477.105.201.158.427.158.677 0 .25-.054.476-.16.677-.106.199-.26.357-.464.474a1.452 1.452 0 0 1-.732.173H.79v1.342H0V11.85Zm2.06 1.714a.795.795 0 0 0 .085-.381c0-.227-.062-.4-.185-.521-.123-.122-.294-.182-.513-.182H.788v1.406h.66a.794.794 0 0 0 .374-.082.574.574 0 0 0 .238-.24Zm2.963.75v1.535H4.23v-1.52L2.89 11.85h.876l.853 1.696h.032l.856-1.696h.855l-1.339 2.464Z"/>
            </svg>
        </div>
        <div class="col-3"><h3>Set up the script</h3></div>
        <div class="col-7"><p> Once you've downloaded the script integrate your code for getting data from the sensors in place of the <strong>get_value()</strong> function. Make sure you have all the libraries installed and once you do run the code
            and you should be able to see a simple GUI to be used for the experiment. The first step to do is to specify a formula by 
            which the data will change given the value of a certain variable
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-2">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="90" height="90" fill="currentColor" class="bi bi-signpost-2-fill" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
                <path d="M7.293.707A1 1 0 0 0 7 1.414V2H2a1 1 0 0 0-1 1v2a1 1 0 0 0 1 1h5v1H2.5a1 1 0 0 0-.8.4L.725 8.7a.5.5 0 0 0 0 .6l.975 1.3a1 1 0 0 0 .8.4H7v5h2v-5h5a1 1 0 0 0 1-1V8a1 1 0 0 0-1-1H9V6h4.5a1 1 0 0 0 .8-.4l.975-1.3a.5.5 0 0 0 0-.6L14.3 2.4a1 1 0 0 0-.8-.4H9v-.586A1 1 0 0 0 7.293.707z"/>
            </svg>
        </div>
        <div class="col-3"><h3>Connect</h3></div>
        <div class="col-7"><p>Create a livestream on the website and connect your board to it through the second input text in the GUI in which you'll need to input the name of the room you've created. Soon after doing that you should see your data
            being displayed in a graph format in the application
        </p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-2">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="90" height="90" fill="currentColor" class="bi bi-send-fill" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
                <path d="M15.964.686a.5.5 0 0 0-.65-.65L.767 5.855H.766l-.452.18a.5.5 0 0 0-.082.887l.41.26.001.002 4.995 3.178 3.178 4.995.002.002.26.41a.5.5 0 0 0 .886-.083l6-15Zm-1.833 1.89L6.637 10.07l-.215-.338a.5.5 0 0 0-.154-.154l-.338-.215 7.494-7.494 1.178-.471-.47 1.178Z"/>
            </svg>
        </div>
        <div class="col-3"><h3>Data Exchange</h3></div>
        <div class="col-7"><p>During the experiment you will be able to ask questions with multiple choice answers to all the users connected. You can decide to save the answers at any point and retrieve them through the last button
            in the GUI which will get and display those answers.
        </p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col-2">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="90" height="90" fill="currentColor" class="bi bi-people-fill" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
                <path d="M7 14s-1 0-1-1 1-4 5-4 5 3 5 4-1 1-1 1H7zm4-6a3 3 0 1 0 0-6 3 3 0 0 0 0 6z"/>
                <path fill-rule="evenodd" d="M5.216 14A2.238 2.238 0 0 1 5 13c0-1.355.68-2.75 1.936-3.72A6.325 6.325 0 0 0 5 9c-4 0-5 3-5 4s1 1 1 1h4.216z"/>
                <path d="M4.5 8a2.5 2.5 0 1 0 0-5 2.5 2.5 0 0 0 0 5z"/>
            </svg>
        </div>
        <div class="col-3"><h3>Digital Twins</h3></div>
        <div class="col-7"><p>The program will compile the average value of the answers and send back a new 'value' for the data based on the previously typed formula which will
            trigger a new graph to be display in order for all the connected users to compare the sensors' data and the one from the formula
        </p></div>
    </div>
